     <div type="poem">
   <head>To the true M<seg rend="sup">r</seg>. in his Art, B. Ionson.</head>
   <l>FOrgiue thy friends; they would, but cannot praise,</l>
   <l>Inough' the wit, art, language of thy <hi>PLAYES:</hi>
   </l>
   <l>Forgiue thy foes; they will not praise thee. Why?</l>
   <l>Thy Fate hath thought it best, they should enuy.</l>
   <l>Faith, for thy <hi>FOXES</hi> sake, forgiue then those</l>
   <l>Who are nor worthy to be friends, nor foes.</l>
   <l>Or, for their owne braue sake, let them be still</l>
   <l>Fooles at thy mercy, and like what they will,</l>
   <closer>
      <signed>I. F.</signed>
   </closer>
</div>
